## Hand Pose & Gesture Detection (Vision framework)

**Framework setup:** Use `AVCaptureVideoDataOutput` for continuous camera frames. Set `setSampleBufferDelegate` on a background queue and store the latest `CMSampleBuffer` in a thread-safe property (use `NSLock`). On user trigger (button tap, countdown end), read the stored buffer and run Vision on it — do not run Vision on every incoming frame.

**CRITICAL — VNImageRequestHandler orientation:**
Always use `.right` for BOTH front and back camera:
```swift
let handler = VNImageRequestHandler(cvPixelBuffer: pixelBuffer, orientation: .right)
```
Never use `.leftMirrored` for the front camera. Although `.leftMirrored` seems correct for mirroring, it inverts the Y-axis relationship between fingertips and knuckles in AVFoundation's native portrait buffer — causing extended fingers to have LOWER Y than their knuckles. This makes `isExtended()` always return false, classifying every gesture as Rock. Use `.right` for both cameras: gesture accuracy is unaffected (only X-axis is mirrored, which doesn't matter for finger extension detection), and Y remains consistent.

**Camera flip support:**
To support front/back camera switching, keep an `isFrontCamera: Bool` property on the detector (or pass it as a parameter). Both cameras use `.right` orientation for Vision. The camera flip only affects which `AVCaptureDevice` is active — it does NOT change the Vision orientation. Wire the flip button to a `flipCamera()` method on `CameraManager` that swaps the device input (see camera-capture skill for the full camera switching pattern):
```swift
// In CameraManager:
func flipCamera() {
    sessionQueue.async { [weak self] in
        guard let self else { return }
        let newPos: AVCaptureDevice.Position = self.currentPosition == .front ? .back : .front
        guard let device = AVCaptureDevice.default(.builtInWideAngleCamera, for: .video, position: newPos),
              let newInput = try? AVCaptureDeviceInput(device: device) else { return }
        self.session.beginConfiguration()
        if let old = self.currentInput { self.session.removeInput(old) }
        if self.session.canAddInput(newInput) {
            self.session.addInput(newInput)
            self.currentInput = newInput
            DispatchQueue.main.async { self.currentPosition = newPos }
        }
        self.session.commitConfiguration()
    }
}
```
Add a flip button to the UI in the top corner:
```swift
Button(action: { cameraManager.flipCamera() }) {
    Image(systemName: "camera.rotate.fill")
        .font(.title2)
        .foregroundStyle(.white)
        .padding(12)
        .background(.ultraThinMaterial, in: Circle())
}
```

**Joint name constants — use exactly these VNHumanHandPoseObservation.JointName values:**
- Thumb: `.thumbTip`, `.thumbCMC`
- Index finger: `.indexTip`, `.indexMCP`
- Middle finger: `.middleTip`, `.middleMCP`
- Ring finger: `.ringTip`, `.ringMCP`
- Little (pinky) finger: `.littleTip`, `.littleMCP`

**Reading a joint point:**
```swift
guard let tip = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.indexTip),
      tip.confidence >= 0.7 else { return }
let x = tip.location.x  // normalized 0-1
let y = tip.location.y  // normalized 0-1, increases UPWARD when using .right orientation
```
With `.right` orientation, Vision coordinates have origin at bottom-left and Y increases upward. A fingertip that is extended ABOVE its knuckle has a HIGHER Y value.

**Finger extension logic — tipY > mcpY when using .right orientation:**
```swift
private func isExtended(tip: VNRecognizedPoint, mcp: VNRecognizedPoint) -> Bool {
    tip.confidence >= 0.7 && mcp.confidence >= 0.7 && tip.location.y > mcp.location.y
}
```
This works correctly for both front and back camera when using `.right` orientation.

**Rock / Paper / Scissors gesture definitions:**
```swift
enum RPSGesture: String {
    case rock = "Rock", paper = "Paper", scissors = "Scissors", unknown = "Unknown"
}

private func classifyGesture(from observation: VNHumanHandPoseObservation) -> RPSGesture {
    guard let indexTip  = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.indexTip),
          let indexMCP  = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.indexMCP),
          let middleTip = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.middleTip),
          let middleMCP = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.middleMCP),
          let ringTip   = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.ringTip),
          let ringMCP   = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.ringMCP),
          let littleTip = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.littleTip),
          let littleMCP = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.littleMCP),
          let thumbTip  = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.thumbTip),
          let thumbCMC  = try? observation.recognizedPoint(.thumbCMC)
    else { return .unknown }

    let indexUp  = isExtended(tip: indexTip,  mcp: indexMCP)
    let middleUp = isExtended(tip: middleTip, mcp: middleMCP)
    let ringUp   = isExtended(tip: ringTip,   mcp: ringMCP)
    let pinkyUp  = isExtended(tip: littleTip, mcp: littleMCP)
    let thumbUp  = isExtended(tip: thumbTip,  mcp: thumbCMC)

    // Paper: all 5 extended
    if indexUp && middleUp && ringUp && pinkyUp && thumbUp { return .paper }
    // Rock: all 4 fingers folded (thumb excluded — thumb position varies too much between users)
    if !indexUp && !middleUp && !ringUp && !pinkyUp { return .rock }
    // Scissors: index + middle extended, ring + pinky folded
    if indexUp && middleUp && !ringUp && !pinkyUp { return .scissors }
    return .unknown
}
```

**Error handling — no hand detected:**
If `request.results` is nil or empty, set a user-visible `statusMessage`: `'No hand detected — hold your hand open in front of the camera and try again.'` Never silently fail; always publish the status to the UI via `@Published var statusMessage: String`.

**Confidence threshold:** Require `confidence >= 0.7` for every joint used in classification. If any joint falls below 0.7, return `.unknown`. Lower thresholds cause unreliable tip/knuckle comparisons.

